o a specific contemporary anxiety: globalization, terrorism, and the end of civilization. Schweitzer considers how these fears, stoked by both fictional outbreak narratives and official sources, have influenced the ways Americans relate to their neighbors, perceive foreigners, and regard social institutions. Looking at everything from I Am Legend to The X Files to World War Z, this book examines how outbreak narratives both excite and horrify us, conjuring our nightmares while letting us indulge in fantasies about fighting infected Others. Going Viral thus raises provocative questions about the cost of public paranoia and the power brokers who profit from it. Supplemental Study Materials for "Going Viral": https://www.rutgersuniversitypress.org/going-viral-dahlia-schweitzer Dahlia Schweitzer- Going Viral: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5xF0V7WL9ow  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aApocalypse in mass media. 0aEpidemics in mass media. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  a24.  a28 days later.  aEbola.  aI am Legend.  aSARS.  aWorld War Z.  aX FIles.  aanxiety.  adisease.  aglobalism.  aoutbreak.  apandemic.  aplague.  asurvivors.  aterrorism.  aviral.  avirus.  awalking dead.  azombie.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813593180zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813593180423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813593180.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11